"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ecclesiastes chapters 5–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ecclesiastes-5-9.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ecclesiastes.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ecclesiastes.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ecclesiastes' הֶבֶל (hebel = vapor/breath/vanity) is the hermeneutical lens;
  Christ's resurrection is the answer to the limit that vapor names.
- Ch 5:1 "house of God" → Jesus as the true temple (John 2:21); temple worship
  points forward to the one mediator (1 Tim 2:5).
- Ch 7:20 "no righteous person on earth who always does good" is not a merely
  rhetorical observation — Romans 3:10 picks it up as scriptural proof of universal
  sin; Christ is the single exception.
- Ch 7:29 "God made human beings upright but they have gone in search of many
  devices" = the Fall in Wisdom idiom; Christ as the second Adam undoes this search.
- Ch 8:1 "who is like the wise man?" → Christ as the Wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:24, 30).
- Ch 9:14–16 poor wise man who saves the city but is forgotten = a shadow of Christ
  despised and rejected but the true deliverer (Isa 53:3).
- For genealogical or purely transitional verses, a brief 'theme' or 'revelation of
  God' entry is used rather than forcing a direct type.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ECCLESIASTES = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: the command to guard one\'s steps approaching the house of God — to come near to listen rather than to sacrifice carelessly — anticipates the one who replaces the temple entirely (John 2:19–21). Jesus, the true temple and the one mediator (1 Tim 2:5), is the destination that all temple-approach imagery points toward. The caution against the sacrifice of fools is answered in Christ\'s one sufficient sacrifice (Heb 10:14).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The vast asymmetry between the creature and God — "God is in heaven and you are on earth; let your words be few" — defines the problem of access that the Incarnation resolves. Christ, who is both in heaven and on earth, the eternal Word who speaks from the Father\'s side (John 1:18), is the one in whom the creature\'s words are received and the divine word fully given. The theme of divine transcendence here points toward the need for a mediator.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The revelation of God: even the governance of words and dreams reflects the order of a God who sees through human noise to the heart. This wisdom teaching is part of the larger OT picture of God\'s sovereign discernment — which the NT presents as fully expressed in Christ, who knows what is in a person and needs no testimony (John 2:25).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The theme: vow-keeping before God reflects the covenantal seriousness of the God who holds his people to their word — and who himself keeps every covenant promise. The NT presents this fulfillment in Christ, in whom all the promises of God find their "Yes" (2 Cor 1:20). The instruction not to delay in fulfilling vows points toward the one who fulfilled every obligation perfectly on behalf of a people who could not.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The theme: better not to make a vow than to vow and not fulfill — a principle of integrity before God. Christ embodies total integrity and the fulfillment of every commitment; in him, the gap between promise and performance that mars human religion is closed.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theme: the mouth that leads into sin and invites divine anger names the problem of human speech before God. Christ is the Word who speaks only what the Father gives (John 12:49) and whose words do not bring judgment but life — and whose intercessory work covers the failures of his people\'s speech before God.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme: "Fear God" — the closing word after surveying the futility of many dreams and words — is the Wisdom tradition\'s fundamental orientation, one that the NT presents as properly directed toward the one in whom God is fully revealed. The fear of God that begins wisdom (Prov 1:7) is the fear that, in the NT, takes the form of reverent submission to Christ as Lord (Phil 2:10–11).</p>',
    "8": '<p>The revelation of God: oppression perpetuated through hierarchies of officials — each covered by a higher — is one face of the fallen order that cries out for a judge above all earthly authorities. Christ as the Lord of lords and Judge of the living and dead (Acts 10:42) stands over every human hierarchy and will vindicate the oppressed poor (Jas 5:4).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The theme: even kings benefit from cultivated land — even the greatest earthly power is bound to the created order and dependent on what the earth yields. This leveling observation participates in the OT wisdom theme of created dependence, which the NT presents as the frame within which Christ the Lord chose to enter as one who ate and drank and was hungry — taking his place within the creaturely order he sustains.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The theme: the insatiability of the lover of money — never satisfied with wealth — names the disordered desire that Ecclesiastes traces throughout. Christ\'s teaching names mammon as the rival to God (Matt 6:24), and Paul declares contentment in all circumstances as possible only "through Christ who strengthens me" (Phil 4:13). The vapor of wealth is answered by "true riches" (Luke 16:11).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The theme: as goods multiply, so do those who consume them — wealth grows a following but not a self. This observation about the futility of accumulation points toward the "better things" (Heb 11:16) that do not multiply consumption but multiply participation in the divine life; Christ promises treasure that cannot be consumed or taken away (Matt 6:20).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The theme: the sweet sleep of the laborer against the sleepless anxiety of the wealthy restless — wealth that brings no rest names the fallen condition in which human security is placed in the wrong thing. Christ offers the rest that wealth cannot purchase (Matt 11:28–30); the one who trusts him can sleep in peace (Ps 4:8).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The revelation of God: wealth hoarded at the owner\'s own expense — a grievous evil observed under the sun — participates in the OT critique of false security in possessions. The NT presents Christ\'s parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16–21) as the sharp edge of this Ecclesiastes observation, and Paul warns that those who desire to be rich fall into temptation (1 Tim 6:9). Hoarding rather than holding loosely is the diagnostic of a heart not anchored in Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The theme: riches lost in a bad venture and a son with nothing — the nakedness of failed inheritance. The fathers who cannot pass wealth to their children reflect the universal limitation of earthly inheritance, against which stands Christ who has secured an inheritance "imperishable, undefiled, and unfading" for those born again into his family (1 Pet 1:4).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: "As he came from his mother\'s womb, so he will leave — naked." This most universal of limits — one cannot take anything from this life — is what Christ assumes and transforms. He entered the world in poverty (2 Cor 8:9) and left it on a cross, having taken nothing material. But through his resurrection he carries humanity into permanent participation in the divine life — the one who was naked on the cross now clothes his people in righteousness (Rev 3:18).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The theme: laboring for the wind — the nihilistic possibility that effort produces nothing lasting — is precisely what the resurrection forecloses. Paul draws on exactly this Ecclesiastes register in 1 Cor 15:58: "Your labor in the Lord is not in vain" — the antidote to laboring for wind is laboring in the one who has overcome death and promises his work will stand.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The revelation of God: eating in darkness, burdened with sickness, vexation, and anger — life consumed by its own weight — names the groaning condition that Paul names in Romans 8:22. Christ bore this darkness in Gethsemane and on the cross; his resurrection is the first movement of creation\'s own liberation from this bondage (Rom 8:21).</p>',
    "18": '<p>The theme: Qohelet\'s "good and fitting" — to eat and drink and find enjoyment in one\'s labor as one\'s God-given portion — is a limited but real good. The NT affirms the goodness of created enjoyment (1 Tim 4:3–4) but locates the permanent version of this gift in Christ; Paul\'s "whatever you do, do it to the glory of God" (1 Cor 10:31) transforms the portioned enjoyment of Ecclesiastes into participation in the life of the age to come.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The theme: when God gives someone the capacity to enjoy wealth and labor — "that is a gift of God." The ability to receive creation\'s goods as gift rather than anxiety is itself a grace, one that the NT anchors in knowing the Giver. Christ, in whom God\'s generosity is fully expressed (Jas 1:17), is the one in whom his people learn contentment and enjoyment as a form of worship (Phil 4:11–12).</p>',
    "20": '<p>The theme: God keeping the heart occupied with joy so that one does not brood over fleeting years — the divine gift of present-moment joy. Christ embodies and mediates this joy: "These things I have spoken to you so that my joy may be in you and your joy may be complete" (John 15:11). The brooding over transience that Ecclesiastes diagnoses is answered in the one who says "I am the resurrection and the life" (John 11:25).</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>The revelation of God: God\'s observation of evil widespread among human beings — the opening of the chapter — assumes the divine moral clarity that sees what is wrong in creation. The NT presents Christ as the one through whom this divine judgment becomes redemptive rather than merely condemning (John 3:17).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The theme: God gives wealth, riches, and honor — yet withholds the capacity to enjoy it, so a stranger devours it. This disconnection between blessing and enjoyment names a specifically theological problem: the good of creation turned to bitter vapor by the absence of the ability to receive it. Christ, the one who is himself the fullness of God\'s blessing (Eph 1:3), gives his people not only good things but the Spirit who enables them to receive creation\'s goods with thanksgiving (1 Tim 4:4).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The theme: the man who cannot fill himself with good things and receives no burial — worse than a stillborn — represents the extreme case of a life without real participation in created goodness. Against this, Christ is the "resurrection and the life" who promises not existence without fullness but abundant life (John 10:10). He is also the one who received proper burial (Matt 27:57–60), and who promises his people a resurrection body.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The theme: the stillborn comes in vapor and departs in darkness, its name buried in darkness — the limit of a life that never registered. Christ, whose own name is above every name (Phil 2:9), names and knows each of his own; no life in him departs unnamed into darkness (John 10:3).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The revelation of God: the stillborn finds more rest than the one who lived long without good. The theme of rest — what constitutes true rest — runs through Wisdom literature into Hebrews, where the "rest that remains for the people of God" is entered through Christ, who himself rested on the seventh day (Heb 4:9–10). The rest the stillborn finds by not enduring a vapor-life is the shadow of the eternal rest Christ secures through his finished work.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theme: "does not everyone go to the same place in the end?" — the leveling force of death that all human diversity cannot escape. Christ transforms this universal limit: his resurrection means that for his people, "the same place" at the end is not merely death but life out of death (Rom 6:8).</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme: all labor toward filling the mouth, yet the appetite is never satisfied — the structural insatiability of the creature that no earthly labor can resolve. Christ as the Bread of Life (John 6:35) answers this: "Whoever comes to me will never be hungry, and whoever believes in me will never be thirsty." The satiation Qohelet cannot find under the sun is given in the one who comes from above.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The theme: what advantage does the wise person have over the fool in any final sense? Wisdom gives navigational skills but not ultimate escape from the common fate. The NT\'s answer is that wisdom finds its ultimate advantage in Christ: "God has made him to be for us wisdom" (1 Cor 1:30), and this wisdom leads through death to resurrection, not merely through life more skillfully.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The theme: better what the eyes can actually see than the restless wandering of desire — a limited commendation of the present moment over restless projection. This theme of presence over projection finds its NT deepening in Christ\'s command not to worry about tomorrow (Matt 6:34), and Paul\'s learning of contentment in whatever state he is in (Phil 4:11) through Christ who strengthens.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The revelation of God: "no one can contend with one far more powerful" — the sovereignty of God over the creature stands firm. Whatever is named is already known and subject to the one who named it (Gen 2:19). The NT presents Christ as the one through whom and for whom all things were created and in whom they hold together (Col 1:16–17) — the one who is "far more powerful" taking on flesh without surrendering his sovereignty.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The theme: the more words, the more futility — a principle that the prologue of John inverts. The eternal Word, through whom all things were made (John 1:3), enters the world not to multiply futility but to resolve it; he is the Word that does not return empty (Isa 55:11). The futility of human words is healed by the one Word that carries the weight of divine meaning.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The theme: "who knows what is truly good for a person" and "who can tell anyone what will happen after they are gone?" — the double unknowing of mortal existence. Christ answers both: he is the Way, the Truth, and the Life who defines what is truly good (John 14:6), and he is the first to return from the dead and report what lies beyond (1 Cor 15:20). The two questions Qohelet poses as unanswerable are answered in the resurrection.</p>'
  },
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>The theme: "a good name is better than fine perfume, and the day of death than the day of birth." The preference for the day of death over the day of birth — counterintuitive wisdom — anticipates the NT\'s valuation of death transformed by resurrection: Paul echoes this when he says "to die is gain" (Phil 1:21). Jesus\' name, poured out like perfume (Song 1:3), is the name above every name, the good name that cannot be taken away (Phil 2:9).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The theme: it is better to go to the house of mourning than the house of feasting, for death is the end of every person and the living should take it to heart. Jesus goes to both: he weeps at Lazarus\' grave (John 11:35) and feasts with sinners (Luke 15:2). His Beatitudes — "Blessed are those who mourn, for they will be comforted" (Matt 5:4) — take up this Ecclesiastes commendation of the house of mourning and add the resurrection comfort Qohelet could not yet see.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The theme: sorrow is better than laughter, for a sad face does the heart good. The wisdom that suffering produces depth rather than shallowness runs through the Psalms of lament, the Servant Songs, and Hebrews: Jesus is "acquainted with grief" (Isa 53:3) and "learned obedience through what he suffered" (Heb 5:8). The NT does not abolish this wisdom but anchors it in the one whose sorrow was the world\'s healing.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The theme: the wise heart is drawn to the house of mourning, the fool\'s to the house of mirth. Wisdom that refuses to evade grief is the posture of the prophets and, ultimately, of Christ, who does not avoid Jerusalem and the cross but sets his face toward them (Luke 9:51). The Wisdom of God takes the path of mourning willingly.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The revelation of God: it is better to hear the rebuke of the wise than the song of fools — a Wisdom principle that recurs in Proverbs (Prov 27:6). Christ is the wise teacher whose rebuke — "woe to you" — is better for those who receive it than any flattery; the prophetic tradition of hard truth-telling climaxes in him who speaks the word that judges and saves (Heb 4:12).</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theme: the crackling of thorns under a pot — the fool\'s laughter — bright and quick and fruitless. This image of ephemeral noise has its NT counterpart in Paul\'s "noisy gong or clanging cymbal" (1 Cor 13:1) — the person who has gifts but not love. Love, which Christ embodies and commands, is the substance that outlasts the noise.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The revelation of God: oppression makes a fool of a wise man; a bribe corrupts the heart — the social forces that undo wisdom. Christ\'s own trial is the extreme case: oppression and bribes (the thirty pieces of silver) corrupt the judgment of the powerful against the Wise One. His cross is the point where human corruption reaches its nadir and divine wisdom turns it to redemption (1 Cor 1:25).</p>',
    "8": '<p>The theme: the end of a matter is better than its beginning; patience of spirit is better than pride. Paul\'s "patient endurance" and Hebrews\'s "endure to the end" draw on this wisdom principle. Christ himself endured to the end, and the letter to the Hebrews presents his completion — "It is finished" (John 19:30) — as the end-is-better-than-beginning principle taken to its ultimate expression.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The theme: do not be hasty to become angry, for anger rests in the lap of fools. Christ embodies this in his "slow to anger" character (Exod 34:6 describes the God of whom he is the full expression), and James picks up the Ecclesiastes wisdom directly: "Be slow to speak and slow to become angry" (Jas 1:19). The one who could have called twelve legions of angels (Matt 26:53) chose patience instead.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The theme: "do not say, \'Why were the former days better than these?\'" — the wisdom against nostalgic retreat. The NT does not commend nostalgia for the old covenant but forward movement into the new: Christ is the new thing God is doing (2 Cor 5:17), and the one who looks back after putting his hand to the plow is not fit for the kingdom (Luke 9:62).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The theme: wisdom like an inheritance is a good thing, benefiting those who see the sun. In the NT, the inheritance is not wisdom as an abstract quality but "the wisdom of God" who is Christ (1 Cor 1:24), the inheritance secured by the Spirit as down payment (Eph 1:14). The "seeing the sun" language resonates with the Johannine light motif: Christ as the light of the world (John 8:12).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The theme: wisdom and money both protect, but wisdom "preserves the life of its possessor." The one who possesses wisdom-who-is-Christ has not just navigational advantage but life itself: "Whoever finds me finds life and obtains favor from the LORD" (Prov 8:35 — Wisdom speaking). The NT identifies this Wisdom as Christ (Col 2:3, where all treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden in him).</p>',
    "13": '<p>A shadow: "Consider what God has done — who can straighten what he has made crooked?" This fundamental acknowledgment of divine sovereignty over reality — even crooked reality — anticipates both the NT\'s recognition of the fallen world and its proclamation that Christ will ultimately make all things new (Rev 21:5). What no human hand can straighten, the one through whom all things were created can restore (Acts 3:21).</p>',
    "14": '<p>The revelation of God: "God has made both the one and the other" — good times and bad, prosperity and adversity — "so that no one can discover what the future holds." This divine hiddenness of the future is part of the creaturely condition; the NT does not promise foreknowledge but promises the presence of the one who holds the future: "I know the plans I have for you" (Jer 29:11), and in Christ, the one who is the same yesterday, today, and forever (Heb 13:8) is with his people in both the good and the bad.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The theme: in futile days, the righteous perish in righteousness and the wicked live long — the observed injustice that cries out for resolution. The psalms of lament make this same cry; the NT\'s answer is the cross and resurrection. Christ, the uniquely righteous one, perishes in his righteousness — and the resurrection is God\'s vindication that righteousness is not ultimately extinguished but exalted (Phil 2:9). The final judgment will reverse every apparent injustice (Rev 20:12–13).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The revelation of God: "Do not be excessively righteous — why should you ruin yourself?" Qohelet\'s pragmatic counsel against hyper-scrupulosity is different from the NT\'s call to righteousness, but both address the human tendency to seek security through moral performance. The NT\'s resolution is not moderate righteousness but imputed righteousness: the "righteous" one is not the person who has achieved enough but the one who trusts in Christ (Rom 4:5; Phil 3:9).</p>',
    "17": '<p>The revelation of God: "Do not be excessively wicked — why die before your time?" The pragmatic boundary against self-destruction through wickedness assumes that death is the consequence of wickedness — a truth that the NT grounds in the deeper reality of sin and death as connected (Rom 6:23). Christ\'s death is the place where this connection is broken for those who are in him.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The theme: grasping both wisdom and not-releasing-the-other, "for the one who fears God will avoid both extremes" — the fear of God as the axis that holds wisdom together. The NT presents Christ as the one who "feared God" (Heb 5:7) perfectly, the embodiment of the wisdom that avoids every extreme, and the one who mediates the fear-of-God that is the beginning of wisdom (1 Cor 1:30).</p>',
    "19": '<p>The theme: wisdom strengthens the wise more than ten rulers — wisdom as practical strength beyond political power. Christ is the one in whom true strength resides, the one who is strong when his followers are weak (2 Cor 12:9–10), and in whom wisdom is not an achievement but a gift (Jas 1:5). Ten rulers cannot match what the Wisdom of God secures for his people.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Direct: "There is no righteous person on earth who always does good and never sins" — a foundational assertion that Paul quotes directly in Romans 3:10–12 as scriptural proof of universal sinfulness. Christ alone is the exception to this universal: he who knew no sin (2 Cor 5:21) becomes sin for us so that we might become the righteousness of God in him. This verse is one of the OT texts most directly absorbed into the NT\'s account of why Christ\'s righteousness is necessary.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The theme: do not pay attention to everything people say — you may hear your servant cursing you. The wisdom of selective attention to criticism, combined with self-awareness that one has done the same, is the creaturely limitation of moral consistency that v.20 names. Christ, who is spoken against throughout his ministry and trial, hears cursing without retaliating (1 Pet 2:23) — absorbing the full weight of human criticism rather than being destroyed by it.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The theme: "your own heart knows that you too have cursed others many times" — the self-implicating move of Wisdom that removes any pretense of moral superiority. The NT deepens this in Matthew 7:1–5: the speck and the log; and Paul: "all have sinned" (Rom 3:23). No one can stand in moral judgment; only the one who has never cursed another — Christ — can both absorb criticism and forgive the critics.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The theme: "I said I will be wise — but wisdom was far from me." The failure of the self-improvement project to secure wisdom is the Ecclesiastes analogue to Paul\'s "wretched man that I am" in Romans 7. The wisdom that Qohelet cannot capture through effort is the wisdom the NT presents as a person — Christ — who must be received as gift (1 Cor 1:30) rather than achieved by resolve.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The theme: "whatever exists is far off and utterly deep — who can discover it?" The epistemic limit of the human knower before the depths of reality is resolved only in the NT\'s claim that God has revealed his deep purposes in Christ: "the deep things of God" are known through the Spirit (1 Cor 2:10), and in Christ "are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3). What is far off and deep is made near in the Incarnation.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The revelation of God: Qohelet\'s turning of the mind to understand wisdom and the explanation of things, to know that wickedness is folly and foolishness is madness — the prophetic dimension of the investigation. Christ is the one who performs the definitive diagnosis of human wickedness and folly, not by philosophical analysis but by entering it, absorbing its consequence, and rising above it (1 Cor 1:18–25).</p>',
    "26": '<p>The theme: the woman whose heart is a trap and hands are chains — "more bitter than death" — functions in Wisdom literature as the personification of deadly folly (Prov 7:27; 9:18). The one who pleases God escapes her. Christ, who pleased God perfectly (Matt 3:17), is the one who was exposed to every trap and snare of the adversary and emerged unbound — and who liberates those caught (Heb 2:14–15).</p>',
    "27": '<p>The revelation of God: "Here is what I found, says the Preacher, adding one thing to another to find the result" — the investigative process of Wisdom. The NT presents Christ as the one in whom the investigation reaches its end: not the sum of accumulated observations but the one who is himself the Way, the Truth, and the Life (John 14:6).</p>',
    "28": '<p>The theme: "one man in a thousand I have found, but not one woman among all these" — the failed search for a person of integrity in the context of the Wisdom investigation. The hyperbole serves the larger argument: one in a thousand is not enough; the NT\'s claim is that the one needed — perfectly righteous, perfectly wise — has been found in Christ (Heb 7:26: "holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners").</p>',
    "29": '<p>Direct: "God made human beings upright, but they have gone in search of many devices." This verse is the Ecclesiastes account of the Fall — in Wisdom idiom rather than Genesis narrative language, but naming the same reality: original uprightness lost to autonomous human striving. The NT\'s second Adam, Jesus Christ, reverses the "search for many devices" by doing only what the Father shows him (John 5:19), living the uprightness that Adam abandoned. Romans 5:18–19 is the NT commentary on this verse.</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>Direct: "Who is like the wise man? Who else knows the meaning of a matter?" — the rhetorical question that in the OT registers divine incomparability (cf. Mic 7:18 "who is a God like you?") here applied to wisdom itself. Paul identifies Christ as the answer: God has made Christ "to be for us wisdom" (1 Cor 1:30), and in him "are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3). The brightened face that wisdom produces echoes Moses\' shining face and ultimately points to Christ, whose face shines with divine glory (2 Cor 3:18; 4:6).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The theme: keep the king\'s command, because of your oath before God — the obligation of loyalty sworn before the divine witness. Paul\'s instruction to submit to governing authorities (Rom 13:1) and Peter\'s "honor the king" (1 Pet 2:17) carry this Ecclesiastes wisdom into the NT context. Christ himself, the true King, commands loyalty; but the oath before God that undergirds all human authority is ultimately answered in the new covenant in his blood (Luke 22:20).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The revelation of God: do not hurry from the king\'s presence; do not persist in a bad cause — the wisdom of measured withdrawal from power. Christ\'s own navigating of kingly authority — "render to Caesar what is Caesar\'s" (Matt 22:21) — reflects this Wisdom guidance, and his refusal to persist in a bad cause (he could have called legions of angels but did not — Matt 26:53) is the ultimate expression of measured submission.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The theme: "the king\'s word is absolute" — no one says to him "what are you doing?" This characterization of royal authority resonates with the divine sovereignty language of Daniel and Job (Job 9:12; 33:13). Christ, the King of kings (Rev 19:16), has absolute authority — "all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me" (Matt 28:18) — yet he is not an arbitrary monarch but the righteous Judge who has himself submitted to every human authority unto death.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The theme: the one who obeys the king\'s command comes to no harm; the wise heart knows the proper time and method. The NT principle of discerning the right time — kairos — is rooted in this kind of wisdom: "making the most of every opportunity because the days are evil" (Eph 5:16). Christ operates with perfect discernment of time: "My hour has not yet come" (John 2:4), and when the hour arrives, he acts with complete authority.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The revelation of God: every purpose has its proper time and method, though trouble weighs heavily on the human being. The divine ordering of time — which no human can fully know — is made available to God\'s people through Christ, who is the same yesterday, today, and forever (Heb 13:8), and in whom the mystery of timing is not chaos but providential purpose (Eph 1:9–10: the mystery of the fullness of time to unite all things in Christ).</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme: no one knows what is coming, and who can tell how it will come? The epistemic limit of mortal existence before the future is the condition Christ entered. He who "did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped" (Phil 2:6) took on human unknowing — the one through whom all times are created submitted to not-knowing "that day or hour" (Mark 13:32) in his kenotic humility.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Direct: "No one has power over the life-breath to restrain it, and no one has power over the day of death." Paul quotes this register in 1 Corinthians 15: no one can escape death — "the last enemy" — by natural means. Christ\'s resurrection is the direct answer to this universal limit: he alone has "the keys of Death and Hades" (Rev 1:18), the first and only one who has had power over the life-breath that all others must relinquish.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The revelation of God: one person dominating another to their own harm — the cycle of oppressive power. The divine observer noting this oppression is the God who judges between the oppressor and oppressed (Ps 82). Christ enters as the oppressed one (Isa 53:7) and his cross — the ultimate act of domination turned against him — becomes the point of liberation for all oppressed by sin and death (Gal 5:1).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The theme: the wicked buried, soon forgotten in the city where they did wrong — the futility of an evil name. Against the evil name forgotten, Christ\'s good name (Eccl 7:1) is the name above every name (Phil 2:9), exalted precisely because he was humiliated. Those who oppose his people — like the wicked here — will be remembered no more, while those in Christ receive his name and are known eternally.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The revelation of God: "when the sentence for a wrong is not carried out quickly, the human heart is emboldened to do evil" — the psychology of delayed judgment. The NT addresses this directly: "because sentence against an evil deed is not executed speedily, the human heart is fully set to do evil" (Ecc 8:11 stands behind Peter\'s warning that scoffers will say "Where is the promise of his coming?" — 2 Pet 3:3–4). Christ\'s return is the execution of the delayed sentence; the patience of God is his giving time for repentance (2 Pet 3:9).</p>',
    "12": '<p>Direct: "I know that it will go well with those who fear God, who stand in awe before him." This affirmation — that despite the sinner\'s long life and apparent prosperity, good will come to the God-fearer — is the OT covenant conviction. The NT places this on the far side of the cross: it will go well with those who are in Christ, because he has absorbed the fate of the wicked and secured the fate of the righteous (Rom 8:1, 28). The knowledge that it will go well is now anchored not in general principle but in a specific historical event.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Direct: "it will not go well with the wicked, and their days will not lengthen like a shadow, because they do not fear God." This is the covenantal declaration of judgment on the wicked. The NT does not soften but deepens it: the wicked who persist in wickedness apart from Christ face judgment (John 3:36; Rev 20:15). The shadow-metaphor — days lengthening like a shadow before disappearing — matches the NT\'s picture of the brevity of earthly seeming-prosperity against eternal consequence.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The theme: the futility that occurs on earth — the righteous getting what the wicked deserve and vice versa — the observed injustice that is "futility." Christ experienced this directly: the righteous received the wages of the wicked (crucifixion as a criminal), and the wicked received release (Barabbas). His cross is the extreme case of this futility — and the resurrection is God\'s refusal to let it be the final word. The ultimate inversion of unjust inversions comes at the last judgment (Matt 25:31–46).</p>',
    "15": '<p>The theme: Qohelet commends joy — eating, drinking, gladness accompanying work through all the days God has given under the sun. The NT receives this commendation: "whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God" (1 Cor 10:31). Paul\'s instruction to "rejoice always" (Phil 4:4) and the NT\'s persistent commendation of gladness in Christ is the fulfillment of Qohelet\'s limited joy — given full weight by the resurrection and the permanent day beyond the sun.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The revelation of God: the sleepless toil of those who labor day and night in searching — neither day nor night do they sleep — names the exhaustion of the human epistemic project. Christ\'s invitation "Come to me, all who are weary and heavy-laden, and I will give you rest" (Matt 11:28) speaks directly to this sleeplessness. The unceasing labor of knowing is answered in the one who says "I am the truth" (John 14:6).</p>',
    "17": '<p>A shadow: "no one can discover what is done under the sun — no matter how much one labors, they cannot find it out." This is Ecclesiastes\' fundamental epistemological limit. The NT\'s claim is that God has disclosed the mystery hidden for ages — in Christ (Col 1:26–27; Eph 3:3–6). The work of God that no one under the sun could discover has been revealed from above the sun; the mystery is now open in the one who came down from heaven (John 3:13).</p>'
  },
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>The theme: "the righteous and the wise and all they do are in God\'s hands" — a statement of divine sovereignty that is the theological axis of Ecclesiastes 9. The NT deepens this: "neither death nor life... nor things to come... will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord" (Rom 8:38–39). The "hands of God" that hold the righteous are, in the NT, the hands pierced for them — the security is personal and covenantal, not merely providential.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The theme: the same fate comes to everyone — righteous and wicked, clean and unclean, those who sacrifice and those who do not. This leveling force of death is not denied but transcended in the NT: Christ shares the common human fate (Heb 2:14) precisely in order to break it. "Since therefore the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death" (Heb 2:14).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A shadow: "this is the evil in everything under the sun: one fate comes to all; moreover, people\'s hearts are full of evil." The dual problem — universal death and universal sin — is the precise diagnosis that the gospel addresses. Romans 5:12 stands behind this verse: "sin came into the world through one man and death through sin." Christ\'s coming is the direct response to this double evil: he who knew no sin bears the consequence of the sin-filled hearts, and in his resurrection, the one-fate-for-all becomes participation in his resurrection life (Rom 6:23).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The theme: "anyone among the living has hope, for a living dog is better off than a dead lion." Hope attached to biological life — the most minimal basis for hope. The NT transforms this: true hope is not merely being alive but being alive in Christ (Col 1:27, "Christ in you, the hope of glory"). The living dog is better than the dead lion because of the possibility of change, conversion, and encounter with Christ — the one who gives "living hope" through his resurrection (1 Pet 1:3).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The theme: "the living know that they will die, but the dead know nothing, and their memory is forgotten." The limit of death — consciousness ending, memory fading — is the condition Christ entered in his own death, and shattered in his resurrection. The dead who "know nothing" is not the NT\'s final word: "we will not all sleep, but we will all be changed" (1 Cor 15:51). Christ, who "died and came to life again" (Rev 1:18), is the first who having "known nothing" in death now knows all things.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theme: their love, hatred, and envy have all vanished — the dead have no share in anything under the sun. The permanent severance of the dead from earthly participation defines the gravity of death — which is why Christ\'s resurrection, giving him "a share" again in the world (Luke 24:41–43, eating fish with the disciples after the resurrection), is so significant. His resurrection body shares in both worlds; his people will too (1 Cor 15:42–44).</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme: "go, eat your food with gladness and drink your wine with a cheerful heart, for God has already approved what you do." This divine approval — already given — is remarkable: Qohelet commends present enjoyment as already-sanctioned by God. The NT grounds this approval specifically in Christ: those who are in Christ are accepted in the Beloved (Eph 1:6); God\'s approval is not in doubt for the one who is in Christ. The gladness commanded here is the gladness of those who know their standing before God is secure.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The theme: "let your clothing always be fresh and white, and your head not lack for oil" — the imagery of festive readiness, the well-dressed participant in a celebration. The NT\'s eschatological dimension takes this imagery and gives it weight: the white garments of the saints (Rev 7:9, 3:4) and the anointing of the Spirit (1 John 2:27; 2 Cor 1:21–22) are the permanent versions of the fresh clothing and oil that Qohelet commends for mortal days. Christ is the one who clothes his people in righteousness (Isa 61:10).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The theme: "enjoy life with the wife you love throughout all your fleeting days... for that is your portion." The commendation of marital love as one\'s portion under the sun is the created-good that Paul affirms as holy and undefiled when received with thanksgiving (1 Tim 4:3–4; Heb 13:4). The NT adds the eschatological frame: marriage is the shadow (Eph 5:31–32) of the permanent union between Christ and his church — the portion under the sun pointing forward to the eternal feast.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Direct: "Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with all your strength, for there is no work, no planning, no knowledge, no wisdom in the grave." Paul quotes this urgency in his own resurrection-grounded work: "Therefore, my beloved brothers and sisters, be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the work of the Lord, knowing that in the Lord your labor is not in vain" (1 Cor 15:58). The resurrection transforms the urgency of Ecclesiastes 9:10: work with all your strength because there is no work in the grave — and the resurrection means the grave is not the end.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The theme: the race is not won by the swift, nor the battle by the strong — time and chance happen to all. This observation that human excellence is not determinative resonates with the NT\'s consistent subversion of human advantage: "God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong" (1 Cor 1:27). Christ himself does not win by conventional strength but through apparent weakness; the cross is the extreme case of "time and chance" overrunning apparent advantage — and being overrun in turn by resurrection.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The theme: no one knows when their hour will come — people are trapped at some evil moment when it falls suddenly upon them. Christ speaks of his own "hour" throughout John — "the hour has not yet come" — and when it arrives, it falls upon him suddenly in Gethsemane. Yet unlike those "trapped at some evil moment," he enters his hour willingly (John 10:18). He who walks into the trap that snares all becomes the one who springs it from within, setting the captives free (Heb 2:15).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The revelation of God: wisdom observed and found remarkable — the divine order that places wisdom at work in the world even when it is unrecognized. The Lord who gave wisdom to Solomon (1 Kgs 3) and whose wisdom runs through creation (Prov 8) leaves traces of himself even in Qohelet\'s observations. The remarkable wisdom in this example points toward the One who is wisdom personified (1 Cor 1:30).</p>',
    "14": '<p>The theme: the great siege of the small city by the powerful king — overwhelming force against a vulnerable community. The NT\'s corresponding image is the church in the world: "a city set on a hill" (Matt 5:14), besieged by the powers of darkness, yet unconquerable because "the gates of hell will not prevail against it" (Matt 16:18). The powerful king besieging the small city is the same pattern as the adversary who prowls around like a roaring lion (1 Pet 5:8).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: "a poor wise man was found in the city, and by his wisdom he saved it — yet no one remembered that poor man afterward." This is one of the clearest anticipatory shadows of Christ in Ecclesiastes. The structural correspondence: one poor man whose wisdom saves a community, but who is despised and forgotten. Isaiah 53:3 — "he was despised and rejected by men" — and Luke 4:24 — "a prophet is not accepted in his hometown" — take up this pattern. Christ saves the city (the people of God) through wisdom written in blood, and the one who was not remembered is now the name above every name (Phil 2:9). The shadow here is remarkably precise.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Direct: "wisdom is better than strength, but the poor man\'s wisdom is despised and his words go unheard." Paul cites this logic in 1 Corinthians 1:25: "the foolishness of God is wiser than human wisdom, and the weakness of God is stronger than human strength." The despised wisdom of the poor man is the type; Christ crucified — "to the Jews a stumbling block and to the Gentiles foolishness" (1 Cor 1:23) — is the fulfillment. The words that went unheard are now proclaimed to every nation.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The theme: words spoken quietly by the wise carry more weight than the shouting of a ruler among fools. Christ teaches with quiet authority — "not as the scribes" (Matt 7:29), without theatrical performance. The still, small voice (1 Kgs 19:12) of divine wisdom against the loud noise of earthly power is the pattern of Christ\'s own ministry: not with fanfare but in the back rooms and on hillsides, speaking words that outlasted every shouting ruler of his age.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The theme: wisdom is better than weapons of war, but one fool can undo a great deal of good. The fragility of wisdom in a world where one fool can unravel what wisdom built is the Ecclesiastes picture of history\'s instability. The NT\'s answer is not that wisdom becomes unbeatable by skill but that Christ\'s wisdom — established by resurrection — cannot be undone by any fool. The one who "destroyed the wisdom of the wise" (1 Cor 1:19) by raising the crucified Jesus has secured a wisdom that no fool can undo again.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ecclesiastes')
    merge_comm(existing, ECCLESIASTES)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ecclesiastes', existing)
    print('Ecclesiastes 5–9 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
